image.caption: In a dedicated ward of the Al-Nasser Hospital, babies are treated for malnutrition—they’re just two of the estimated 1.8 million acutely malnourished children under age five. Yemen’s depleted health ministry relies on humanitarian organizations to provide medical care.
image.alt_text: Picture of a woman sitting on a bed next to two babies each on a bed in a hospital

title.text: The World Has Left Yemen to Die

dek.text: Exclusive photos give a rare look inside the country, where civil war has trapped civilians in a life of violence and disease.

image.caption: This aerial picture shows the Flaming Cliffs in the Gobi Desert. Roy Chapman Andrews, who could be called the first fossil hunter, mounted a huge expedition to the Gobi Desert in the early 1920s. There, his team found the first dinosaur ever known to science.
image.credit: Photograph by Johannes Eisele, AFP, Getty
image.alt_text: Picture of Flaming Cliffs in the Gobi Desert

title.text: Would you risk prison for a dinosaur fossil? This man did.

dek.text: The obsession with finding and selling dinosaur fossils lead one hunter into a world he could not escape.

title.text: Our favorite photos from this week—taken by you

dek.text: Each week, our editors choose stunning photos submitted by members of Your Shot, National Geographic's photo community.

images.caption: A long-exposure image captures the brilliant light of a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket as it launched from Vandenberg Air Force Base in California just after sunset on October 7. The image also shows the rocket's booster as it came back to Earth near the launch pad, marking the first time a SpaceX booster has returned to land on the West Coast.
images.credit: Photograph by Glenn Beltz
images.alt_text: Picture of Falcon 9 SpaceX launch.

images.caption: Seen in a new picture from NASA's Spitzer Space Telescope, the Cat's Paw Nebula is a star-forming region that lies inside the Milky Way galaxy. Newborn stars heat up the surrounding gas, which expands to form the bubbles that give the nebula its feline appearance.
images.credit: Photograph by NASA/JPL-Caltech
images.alt_text: Picture of the cat's paw nebula.

images.caption: On October 7, the International Space Station was orbiting about 256 miles above South Australia when a camera on board captured this view of Earth's atmospheric glow framed against the sparkling band of the Milky Way.
images.credit: Photograph by NASA/JSC
images.alt_text: Picture of celestial view of Earth's atmospheric glow and the Milky Way.

images.caption: A false-color infrared image shows the Soyuz MS-10 spacecraft as it launches for the ISS on October 11 carrying NASA astronaut Nick Hague and Roscosmos cosmonaut Alexey Ovchinin. Shortly after the capsule launched, the rocket experienced an anomaly that forced the space travelers to abort and return to Earth. Both men landed safely, but the event sparked NASA and Roscosmos to halt launches to the ISS until December at the earliest.
images.credit: Photograph by NASA/Bill Ingalls
images.alt_text: Picture of soyuz MS-10 spacecraft is seen in this false color infrared image.

images.caption: The Soyuz MS-08 space capsule lands in a remote area of Kazakhstan on October 4. The capsule carried NASA astronauts Andrew Feustel and Richard Arnold along with Roscosmos cosmonaut Oleg Artemyev back to Earth after their six-month mission aboard the ISS.
images.credit: Photograph by MAXIM SHIPENKOV/AFP/Getty Images
images.alt_text: Picture of Soyuz MS-08 space capsule lands in a remote area in Kazakhstan.

images.caption: NASA astronaut Andrew Feustel gets carried to a medical tent shortly after he and two other space travelers returned to Earth on October 4. Feustel, Richard Arnold, and Oleg Artemyev spent 197 days in space as part of the ISS crew.
images.credit: Photograph by NASA/Bill Ingalls

images.caption: A plane and a satellite pass by as a man stargazes at Brimham Rocks in Yorkshire, U.K., during the peak of the annual Orionid meteor shower on October 21.
images.credit: Photograph by Danny Lawson/PA Images via Getty Images
images.alt_text: Picture of a man stargazing in Yorkshire as the Orionid meteor shower reaches its peak.

images.caption: The European Student Earth Orbiter satellite undergoes testing at a European Space Agency facility in the Netherlands. Ten student teams designed and built the instruments for this satellite, which is due to launch later in 2018.
images.credit: Photograph by ESA
images.alt_text: Picture of ESA satellite.

images.caption: The cosmic cascade of dust and gas known as the Ghost Nebula stars in this haunting picture from the Hubble Space Telescope. Nestled in the constellation of Cassiopeia, the nebula is being blasted by radiation from a nearby giant star—the bluish point of light at the center of the distinctive "W" asterism that forms the constellation.
images.credit:
Photograph by NASA, ESA, and STScI

Acknowledgement: H. Arab (University of Strasbourg)
images.alt_text: Picture of nebulae.

images.caption: A rocket launch lights up the night on October 20 as the BepiColombo spacecraft lifts off from the Kourou spaceport in French Guiana. This joint mission between European and Japanese space agencies will study Mercury, the closest planet to the sun, and is due to settle into orbit around its target in 2025.
images.credit: Photography by ESA / S. Corvaja
images.alt_text: Picture of BepiColombo liftoff

images.caption: The barred spiral galaxy known as Messier 95 dazzles in this image from the Hubble Space Telescope. Similar to the structure of our home galaxy, M95 has a bar of dust and gas cutting through its center that is surrounded by an inner ring of matter that is currently forming new stars.
images.credit: Photograph by NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope
images.alt_text: Picture of a spiral galaxy named Messier 95

images.caption: A grinning skull surrounded by blood-red spatter seems to peer out from this picture captured by the ESO’s Very Large Telescope in Chile. The sinister visage is actually an active star-forming region called NGC 2467, otherwise known as the Skull and Crossbones Nebula.
images.credit: Photograph by ESO
images.alt_text: Picture of an active star forming region

images.caption: Hurricane Michael makes landfall over the Florida panhandle as a Category 4 storm, as seen from the ISS on October 10. The National Hurricane Center reported that Michael had maximum sustained winds near 145 miles an hour as it came ashore, creating damaging storm surges.
images.credit: Photograph by NASA
images.alt_text: Picture of Hurricane Michael was captured from the International Space Station

image.caption: Arch Canyon is still protected within Bears Ears National Monument, but other canyons and thousands of Native American archaeological sites now lie outside the monument’s newly reduced—and still contested—borders. The monument is named after the twin buttes on the horizon, which are held sacred by local tribes.

image.caption: The sun rises in Wyoming on male sage grouse strutting their stuff, chests puffed, tails splayed. Their courting arenas, or leks, are clearings in the sagebrush.

title.text: An awkward bird symbolizes the fight over America's West
